'''''Ninja Gaiden''''' is an [[action-adventure game]] developed by [[Team Ninja]] for the [[Xbox]] video game console. It went through five years of development before its release by [[Tecmo]] in 2004. The game was a hit in [[North America]]; it sold 362,441&nbsp;copies in the first month. Reception in [[Japan]], however, was poor; consumers bought around 60,000&nbsp;copies in the four months following its release.

''Ninja Gaiden'' used the name and the main character, [[Ryu Hayabusa]], of the [[Ninja Gaiden (video game)|1990s series]] that ran on the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]]; those were, however, the only direct connections between the two games. The 2004 version of ''Ninja Gaiden'' had a new story that takes place in the settings of another Team Ninja game, the [[Dead or Alive (series)|''Dead or Alive'' series]]. An evil force has raided the Hayabusa village and stolen the Dark Dragon Blade from its care. The player controls Ryu in his quest to avenge the deaths of his clan and to reclaim the stolen blade. The game featured the use of many weapons and magic spells to destroy hordes of enemies.

''Ninja Gaiden'' was the focus of an online series of matches that spanned North America, [[Europe]], and Japan. Record-breaking numbers of players took part and the final took place at [[Tokyo Game Show|Tokyo Game Show 2004]]. The game continued to evolve in the three years following its release through content downloaded from [[Xbox Live]] and re-releases. ''Ninja Gaiden'' has also received much critical acclaim; several critics named it as one of the best and most difficult games ever made.

==Gameplay==
''Ninja Gaiden'' develops its narrative thread through the actions of its player-controlled protagonist, [[Ryu Hayabusa]]. Viewed from a [[Third-person shooter|third person]] over-the-shoulder perspective, in typical [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] fashion Ryu starts the game with basic, low-level abilities and weapons that can be upgraded as he progresses, by discovering or buying items. In keeping with his [[ninja]] persona, his character can interact with the game environment to perform acrobatic feats, such as running along and jumping off walls, swinging from pole to pole, or running across water.<ref name="gsngrev">{{cite web
  | author = [[Greg Kasavin]]
  | title = Ninja Gaiden for Xbox Review
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-02-26
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaiden/review.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

The game world is made up of several distinct regions,<ref name="edge">{{cite journal
  | author = Edge staff
  | year = 2002
  | month = August
  | title = Inside... Tecmo
  | journal = [[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]
  | issue = 113
  | pages = pp. 51&ndash;55
  | publisher = [[Future plc|Future Publishing]]
  | location = Bath, England
  | issn = 1350-1593 }}
</ref> most of which are connected via the city of Tairon, which functions as a hub.<ref name="entdep">{{cite web
  | author = Matt Warner
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = The Entertainment Depot
  | date = 2004-07-16
  | url = http://www.entdepot.com/xbox/ninjagaiden/review.php
  | accessdate = 2008-01-27 }}</ref> Inspired by the mechanics of the ''[[The Legend of Zelda (series)|The Legend of Zelda]]'' video games, access to these regions is obtained by fighting enemies, finding keys, or solving puzzles.<ref name="gsngrev" /><ref name="sigpre">{{cite web
  | author = James Mielke
  | title = Previews: Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2007-01-12
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3156377
  | accessdate = 2008-01-27 }}
</ref> To avoid disrupting its narrative flow, the game hides delays caused by loading a new area into memory by showing [[Cut scene|in game cut scenes]],<ref name="trend">{{cite web
  | author = Ron Burke
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[Gaming Trend]]
  | year = 2004
  | url = http://www.gamingtrend.com/Reviews/review/review.php?ReviewID=96
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref> and [[Japanese dragon|Dragon]] [[bust (sculpture)|busts]] scattered throughout the regions provide the means to save player progress, permitting gameplay to be resumed at a later time.

In addition to the narrative Story Mode, subsequent [[Video game remake|remake]]s ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' and ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' introduced a gameplay variation called Mission Mode. Focused on action rather than character development, this provides combat-based missions set mainly in small areas, where the player's goal is to "destroy all enemies".<ref name="gsngbrev">{{cite web
  | author = [[Greg Kasavin]]
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Black for Xbox Review
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2005-09-20
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaidenblack/review.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> In both Story and Mission modes, game scoring is based on the player's speed in clearing encounters, the number of kills achieved, the number of unused magic spells (or ''ninpos'') remaining at the end, and the amount of cash collected. Players can compare their scores on online ranking boards.<ref name="prosigrev">{{cite web
  | author = Will Freeman
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Review
  | publisher = ''[[Pro-G]]''
  | date = 2007-07-10
  | url = http://www.videogamer.com/ps3/ninja_gaiden_sigma/review.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref>

===Combat system===
Ryu's movements are directed using the console [[gamepad]]. The game's control system, which comprises the left [[analog stick|thumbstick]], two attack buttons, and a block button, was described as "fluid and responsive",<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Alex Kidman
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[CNET]] Australia
  | date = 2004-08-02
  | url = http://www.cnet.com.au/games/xbox/0,239029621,219117552,00.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23
  | quote = This gripping feeling is accentuated by the game's controls, which are both fluid and responsive, whether in the pure platform-like sections (think ''[[Prince of Persia: The Sands of Time]]'', especially when Ryu's running along walls or flipping himself out of pits) or the core of the game's challenge, the combat sections. }}
</ref><ref name="ign_inter">{{cite web
  | author = Aaron Boulding
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: The Interview
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2003-06-25
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/426/426010p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref name="denngb">{{cite web
  | author = Ludwig Kietzmann
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Black
  | publisher = Digital Entertainment News
  | date = 2006-03-23
  | url = http://dignews.com/review.php?story_id=14316
  | accessdate = 2007-08-22 }}
</ref> and ''Ninja Gaiden'' was regarded as having one of the deeper combat engines among [[Xbox]] games at the time, comparing well to the {{nowraplinks}}[[PlayStation 2]]{{nowraplinks end}} action-adventures ''[[God of War (video game)|God of War]]'' and ''[[Devil May Cry (series)|Devil May Cry]]''.<ref name="mech">{{cite web
  | author = Eric Williams
  | title = Combat Canceled: God of War & Action Game Design
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2008-02-15
  | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=17215
  | accessdate = 2008-02-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Tom Orry
  | title = God of War: Chains of Olympus Review
  | publisher = [[Pro-G]]
  | date = 2008-03-28
  | url = http://www.videogamer.com/psp/god_of_war_chains_of_olympus/review.html
  | accessdate = 2008-05-31 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Christian Nutt
  | title = Ninja Gaiden (Xbox)
  | publisher = [[GameSpy]]
  | date = 2004-02-27
  | url = http://xbox.gamespy.com/xbox/ninja-gaiden/499692p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Eric Williams, the designer of the ''God of War'' combat engine, explained that ''Ninja Gaiden'' prohibits players from stopping or changing attacks in mid-stroke. In contrast, ''God of War'' allows players to do so, and ''Devil May Cry'' grants this freedom to certain attacks. Williams said that, compared to those two games, the combat system in ''Ninja Gaiden'' was harder to master; however, it let players fight their computer controlled foes on equal terms.<ref name="mech" />

[[Image:Ninja Gaiden DS Prep.jpg|thumb|200px|left|In ''Ninja Gaiden'', players can draw in 'essences' to launch Ultimate Techniques that allow Ryu to damage enemies without taking damage himself. Click [[Media:Ninja Gaiden DS UT.gif|here]] to watch an Ultimate Technique in action. ]]
''Ninja Gaiden'' features a large selection of weapons for Ryu to wield, each with advantages and disadvantages that affect the way the player approaches combat. These include one-handed swords, such as the Dragon Sword and Kitetsu, which grant quick attacks and a move called the "Flying Swallow", that allows Ryu to leap and slash through enemies. In addition these light weapons allow Ryu to smash foes into the ground and perform his signature Izuna Drop&mdash;a spinning [[Piledriver (professional wrestling)|piledriver]]. Heavy weapons, such as the Dabilahro and the Unlabored Flawlessness, are slow but cause more damage to opponents. With [[flail]]s and [[Staff (stick)|staves]], the player can string together long sequences of attacks, and to engage disant foes Ryu can throw [[shuriken]] and shoot arrows.<ref name="gsngrev" /><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Blade Love
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-02-25
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/494/494669p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

In addition to using standard melee techniques, Ryu can employ 'essences' in combat. These are colored globes of energy that are released on the death of enemies, and absorbed into Ryu's body when he comes into proximity with them. Essences have an important role in general gameplay, acting to heal Ryu, restore his magic, or increase his cash. However, in combat the player can cause Ryu to deliberately draw in essences, which can then be used to unleash powerful attacks known as Ultimate Techniques.<ref name="denngb" /> These techniques deal heavy damage and make Ryu immune to injury for a short time.<ref name="eurong">{{cite web
  | author = Tom Bramwell
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = 2004-03-16
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=54896
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

''Ninja Gaiden'' also provides Ryu with magical spells in the form of ''ninpos''. When activated by the player, these make Ryu cast fireballs, ice storms, or bolts of lightning. Functioning in a similar manner to the bombs or grenades of [[Shoot 'em up|shooter action games]], these spells allow Ryu to inflict heavy damage on enemies while potentially avoiding damage himself.<ref name="ignngrev">{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Review
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-02-27
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/495/495186p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> However, dissatisfied with their programmed visual effects, the [[game director]] [[Tomonobu Itagaki]] wanted to deter players from using ninpos. He therefore tweaked the game to award bonus points when players cleared stages without employing magic.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = James Mielke
  | title = Previews: Ninja Gaiden 2
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2007-11-16
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3164447
  | accessdate = 2007-11-16 }}
</ref>

For Ryu's defense, the player has two options. First, Ryu can stand still and attempt to block attacks. However, certain enemies can break his guard&mdash;either through particularly strong attacks or by [[grappling]] him. The second option is to make Ryu dodge, by rolling away from the attack in a maneuver called "reverse wind".<ref name="denngb" />
<br style="clear:left;"/>

==Plot and setting==
[[Image:NGB Meeting Alma.jpg|thumb|200px|right|''Ninja Gaiden'' draws on real world architectural styles, such as this [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] monastery.]]
''Ninja Gaiden'' is set in the game world of another [[Tecmo]] release, ''[[Dead or Alive (series)|Dead or Alive]]'' (''DOA'').<ref name="teamxbox_int">{{cite web
  | author = César A. Berardini
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Tomonobu Itagaki Interview
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2003-12-05
  | url = http://interviews.teamxbox.com/xbox/701/Ninja-Gaiden-Tomonobu-Itagaki-Interview/p1/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Located mainly in [[Japan]] and the fictional Vigoor Empire, the game draws on [[Japanese architecture#Heian period|Heian period]] structures for its Japanese locales&mdash;a [[ninja]] fortress and village set in the mountains. In contrast the Vigoor Empire, with its capital city of Tairon, is a blend of architectural types from around the world.<ref name="eurong" /> [[Europe]]an-style buildings display [[Arabic language|Arabic]] lettering, and the monastery in Tairon exhibits [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] influences with a vaulted hall, pointed arches, and large stained glass windows. A hidden underground level features statues with the heads of cats, walls covered with carvings, and [[Egyptian hieroglyphs|hieroglyphics]], and [[Team Ninja]] included an [[Mesoamerican pyramids|Aztec pyramid]] and a [[labyrinth]].<ref name="entdep" /> This [[wikt:hodgepodge|hodgepodge]] of styles was the result of Itagaki's deliberate refusal to constrain the game's creative process.<ref name="teamxbox_int" />

===Characters===
{{main|List of Ninja Gaiden characters}}
[[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Ryu Hayabusa 2|Ryu Hayabusa]], the super ninja, is the protagonist of ''Ninja Gaiden''.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = James Mielke 
  | title = Itagaki Talks DOA4 Demo on Live
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2006-07-24
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3152406
  | quote = Tomonobu Itagaki: First of all, I have of course included the eternal heroine, Kasumi, as well as everyone's favorite Super Ninja, Ryu Hayabusa.
  | accessdate = 2007-10-08 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = GameSpy staff 
  | title = Dead or Alive 4 Guys Week #1 (X360)
  | publisher = [[GameSpy]]
  | date = 2005-10-25
  | url = http://xbox360.gamespy.com/xbox-360/dead-or-alive-4/657005p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-10-08 }}
</ref> He is also the only character that players can control in ''Ninja Gaiden''. Itagaki believed that creating extra player characters would distract his team from making a good character out of Ryu.<ref name="gmr">{{cite journal
  | author = James Mielke
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | journal = [[GMR (magazine)|GMR]]
  | publisher = [[Ziff-Davis]]
  | location = California, United States
  | year = 2003
  | month = July
  | issn = 1544-6816
  | quote = Tomonobu Itagaki: We're not really that interested in making supporting characters playable. Right now, we are simply focusing on making the movements and actions of our "Super Ninja" Ryu Hayabusa the coolest on the planet. }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = James Mielke
  | title = Itagaki Hardcore Part 1: The Future of Team Ninja
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2005-09-27
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3144132
  | accessdate = 2007-10-01 }}
</ref> Ryu has a long history with Tecmo; he was the star in the old 1990s ''[[Ninja Gaiden (video game)|Ninja Gaiden]]'' series and was part of the ''DOA'' roster since 1996. His roles in these games played a part in his popularity among fans and the game industry.<ref name="history">{{cite web
  | author = Rus McLaughlin
  | title = IGN Presents The History of Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2008-01-28
  | url = http://retro.ign.com/articles/848/848155p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-01-29 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite video
  | people     = [[ScrewAttack]]
  | date2      = 2007-08-28
  | title      = Top Ten Ninjas
  | url        = http://www.gametrailers.com/player/24269.html
  | format     = swf
  | publisher  = [[GameTrailers]]
  | accessdate = 2008-03-30
  | time       = 05:20 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Jeff "Mr. Nash" Nash
  | title = Weekly Top 10: Best Ninjas
  | publisher = The Armchair Empire
  | date = 2006-03-06
  | url = http://www.armchairempire.com/Features/Weekly-Top-10/best-ninjas.htm
  | accessdate = 2008-03-30 }}
</ref> As ''Ninja Gaiden'' takes place two years before the first ''DOA'' game,<ref name="teamxbox_int" /> it shows events that lead to Ryu becoming the stoic and reliable character in ''DOA''.<ref name="history" />

[[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Supporting characters 2|Rachel]] is the leading female character and [[tragic hero]]ine of the game. She and her twin sister, [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Leaders of the Fiends|Alma]], suffer the blood curse that turns people into [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|fiends]].<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Rachel: It's hard to believe they were ever humans, isn't it?&nbsp;[...] Anyone with susceptibility to the curse, whether they are a saint or a sinner, can succumb to it and become a Fiend. }}
</ref> The Greater Fiend, [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Leaders of the Fiends|Doku]], took advantage of the curse to turn Alma into a fiend. Rachel thinks that there is no cure to this curse. As such, she seeks to kill Alma to redeem her sister's soul. The relationship between the sisters and Doku serves as a [[plot device]] to move the story.<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2007-07-03
  | platform = [[PlayStation 3]]
  | quote = Rachel: I was convinced once that my blood was pure... but then I saw what my pure blood was capable of. I watched as my twin sister was cursed and twisted into a Greater Fiend. Now I know the path I walk is narrow. }}
</ref> Rachel also serves as the occasional [[damsel in distress]] for Ryu to rescue. She is not a player character in ''Ninja Gaiden''. However, players can control her in a few sections of the remake, ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''.<ref name="sigpre" />

Two other characters help the player in the game. [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Supporting characters 2|Ayane]] is a female ninja and one of the ''DOA'' regular cast members. She acts as a guide throughout Ninja Gaiden by giving objectives and tips to the player. The other character is [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Supporting characters 2|Muramasa]]. He is a [[bladesmith]] and has shops spread over the game world. He sells players items and upgrades their weapons. He also gives [[back-story|back-stories]], [[quest (gaming)|quests]], and crucial information; he tells Ryu to find the Dragon Eye jewel at the Hayabusa village to upgrade the Dragon Sword to its full potential.

Team Ninja created many types of enemies for ''Ninja Gaiden''. Itagaki found it more interesting to create nonhuman creatures than to create human soldiers and ninjas.<ref name="giint" /> As such, most of the enemies in the game are fiends, which are humans changed into monsters by the blood curse. Three Greater Fiends lead the fiends against Ryu and play major roles in the story. First, there is Alma. The story between Rachel and her is a major part of the game. Doku is the main [[antagonist]] of the game; he raids the Hayabusa village, steals the Dark Dragon Blade, and causes the discord between the sisters. The last Greater Fiend is [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Leaders of the Fiends|Marbus]] who is responsible for the last set of challenges standing in Ryu's way to the Emperor of the fiends.<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Ryu: So, the Greater Fiends have a soul, don't they?<br />Rachel: [...] There are only three of them, Doku, my sister and another who guards the Emperor. }}
</ref>

Team Ninja based their [[3D modeling|3D computer models]] on real world material; the pistols of the henchman, Gamov, were faithful models of real world handguns. Team Ninja also created the character models based on studies of human anatomy. Besides this, the team hired [[Martial arts|martial artists]] and digitally captured their moves. They did not use the [[motion capture]]s directly for the game. Their animators used these captures as a basis to give a sense of realism to the game characters' exaggerated moves. Team Ninja also gave players the option to customize the player characters; this came as costumes for Ryu and hairstyles for Rachel.<ref name="sigpre" />

===Story===
The story of Ryu and his quest for vengeance spans sixteen chapters. Each chapter starts and ends with a cut scene. At the start of the game, the player takes control of Ryu as he invades the Shadow clan fortress. Ryu is there to visit the clan leader, [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Ninjas|Murai]], who is his uncle. During their chat, Ayane runs in and delivers news of a raid on the Hayabusa village. Ryu fights his way back to his village and encounters Doku who has taken the Dark Dragon Blade and killed Kureha, the Hayabusa [[miko|shrine maiden]]. The encounter ends with Doku cutting Ryu down with the Blade. Before the screen [[Fade (film)|fades out]], it lingers on a [[falcon]] watching over Ryu's body. The falcon is the spiritual animal of the Hayabusas and brings Ryu back to life offscreen.<ref>{{cite journal
  | author = Chris Johnston
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | journal = [[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]
  | publisher = [[Ziff-Davis]]
  | location = California, United States
  | year = 2004
  | month = June
  | issn = 1058-918X
  | url = http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-21191655_ITM
  | accessdate = 2007-09-05
  | quote = Tomonobu Itagaki: Yes, he died. Do you remember the falcon staring at his dead body? That falcon’s spiritual power resurrected him as a soldier of revenge. }}
</ref>

Kureha's death serves as the motivation for Ryu to seek revenge on the raiders.<ref name="gmr" /> He learns from Murai that they were from the Vigoor Empire and hides on a Zeppelin to sneak into the country. Ryu fights through the streets of Tairon, cutting down those who stand in his way. The player also faces several [[boss (video games)|bosses]] in Ryu's rampage through Tairon. These bosses include the three Greater Fiends. Ryu first defeats Alma in a battle that wrecks the city. He leaves Alma to her sister's mercy, but Rachel cannot bring herself to kill Alma.<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Doku: Ah... Rachel. I should kill you now for the pain you've inflicted on Alma, but instead, I shall use you to make her even stronger. It will be your blood, the cursed blood of a twin sister that shall serve to awaken Alma. }}
</ref> Rachel later falls to Doku who prepares to sacrifice her in a ritual to enhance Alma's power. Ryu rescues her with Alma's help and destroys Doku's spirit. Doku, however, casts the blood curse on Ryu with his last breath.<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Spirit Doku: Receive the curse, become a Fiend. }}
</ref> The only way for Ryu to lift the curse is to kill the Emperor. He invades the palace and kills Marbus. This clears the way to the Emperor's personal realm. The player has to clear two successive boss fights to destroy the Emperor. The realm starts to collapse on the Emperor's death and the player has to navigate Ryu [[Jumping puzzle|up a series of ledges]] to escape.

Ryu loses his grip on the recovered Dark Dragon Blade in his escape. It lands at the feet of the Dark Disciple who has been shadowing Ryu throughout the story. The Disciple picks up the Blade and unmasks himself as Murai. He admits that the raid on the Hayabusa village was part of his plan to restore the Blade's evil power with souls gathered from Ryu's quest of vengeance.<ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Dark Disciple: Gamov, so the Dark Dragon grows in power with each killing. }}
</ref><ref>{{cite video game
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | developer = [[Team Ninja]]
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-03-02
  | platform = [[Xbox]]
  | quote = Gamov: Don't you see? The Dark Dragon is now truly an evil blade. His Excellency the Dark Disciple has been waiting for this very moment! }}
</ref> The restored Dark Dragon Blade enhances Murai with its dark powers, setting up the final boss fight. Ryu defeats Murai and shatters the Blade with the True Dragon Sword. He tells Rachel that "It's over ...", turns himself into a falcon, and flies to the Hayabusa village. In the final scene, Ryu places the Dragon Eye back on Kureha's tombstone and disappears into the night. The story of Ninja Gaiden continues in ''[[Ninja Gaiden Dragon Sword]]'' and ''[[Ninja Gaiden II (2008 video game)|Ninja Gaiden II]]''.
<br style="clear:left;"/>

==Development==
In 1999, Team Ninja started work on the "Next-Generation Ninja Gaiden Project".<ref name="history" /> In the first stage of development, they created the game on the [[List of Sega arcade system boards#Sega NAOMI|Sega NAOMI]] arcade system board. The next part of their plan was to move the project to the [[Dreamcast]] console for further development and release. However, this came to a halt when Sega announced the end of Dreamcast product line in 2001.<ref name="edge" /> At this point, Tecmo decided to make ''Ninja Gaiden'' as a launch title for the [[Sony Computer Entertainment|Sony]] {{nowraplinks}}[[PlayStation 2]]{{nowraplinks end}} in the United States.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Sam Kennedy
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Goes PlayStation 2
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 1999-06-03
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/2450994.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Itagaki, however, had other plans; the Team Ninja Leader was impressed with the [[software development kit]]s for the Xbox and pushed for his team to develop games for the [[Microsoft]] console.<ref name="history" /> The company kept silent on this change in development. Hence, Tecmo surprised the games industry when they announced at [[E3 Media and Business Summit|E3 2002]] that ''Ninja Gaiden'' was exclusive to the Xbox.<ref name="armemp">{{cite web
  | author = Aaron "Omni" Simmer
  | title = Xbox Previews: Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = The Armchair Empire
  | date = 2003-04-05
  | url = http://www.armchairempire.com/Previews/Xbox/ninja-gaiden.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> This also surprised the fans; most of them who voted on Tecmo's poll wanted the game on the [[Nintendo]] [[GameCube]].<ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden on PS2?
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2001-06-29
  | url = http://ps2.ign.com/articles/096/096210p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

''Ninja Gaiden'' was Team Ninja's first action title. Its original concept had nothing in common with the old ''[[Ninja Gaiden (video game)|Ninja Gaiden]]'' series.<ref name="wint">{{cite journal
  | author = Xbox Nation staff
  | title = Paradise Lost
  | journal = Xbox Nation
  | publisher = [[Ziff Davis]]
  | location = California, United States
  | issn = 1538-9723
  | year = 2002
  | month = Winter
  | url = http://bellsouthpwp.net/r/a/racerg/itagaki-xbn-winter2002.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}
</ref> Tecmo, however, wanted to link the game with the old series. The old series, which ran on the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], had fans in the [[Western world|West]] who enjoyed Ryu's adventures.<ref name="history" /> If the new game had ties to the old series, it would gain a measure of visibility in the market. Tecmo asked Itagaki to adopt the theme of the old series and to target the foreign market.<ref name="wint" /><ref name="edge" /> Itagaki examined the old series and believed that its violence appealed to the players. He put gory content, such as beheadings, in the Xbox game to keep that spirit.<ref name="edge" /> He also aimed to make the game hard but appealing;<ref name="teamxbox_int" /> it would challenge players on their reflexes rather than on their memories of layouts and timings.<ref name="ign_inter" /> His team also made it a point to make the game flow smoothly with high-quality animations that react quickly to the player's input.<ref name="teamxbox_int" /> As the [[game director]], Itagaki did not follow the story of the old series and created a new one. However, he paid homage to the old series by creating updated versions of foes and special attacks from the old games and placing them in the new game.<ref name="gsngrev" /><ref name="ignngrev" />

In 2004, Tecmo released a [[game demo|demo disc]] of ''Ninja Gaiden'' in Japan. It was bundled with the February 26 issue of ''[[Famitsu|Famitsu Xbox]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Demo Disc
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-01-20
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/473/473498p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The demo let players try the first chapter of the game on two difficulties with a few fully upgraded weapons and ninpos.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Anoop Gantayat
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Demo Busted
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-02-13
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/492/492400p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> On [[March 2]], Tecmo finally released Ninja Gaiden after a year of delays since the first announced release date.<ref name="armemp" /><ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Release Date Locked Down
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2004-02-24
  | url = http://www.armchairempire.com/videogame-news/Xbox/Febraury-2004/ninja-gaiden-release-date.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Still On Track
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2003-09-19
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/450/450798p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-04-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = More Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2003-12-01
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/442/442537p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-04-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = IGN staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Delay
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-01-29
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/481/481455p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-04-21 }}
</ref>

===Post-release===
Team Ninja kept working on the project after its release. They wanted to push the envelope of the action genre for their first such title as far as they could.<ref name="giint">{{cite web
  | author = Billy Berghammer
  | title = An Interivew With Tomonobu Itagaki
  | publisher = ''[[Game Informer]]''
  | date = 2004-07-27
  | url = http://www.gameinformer.com/News/Story/200407/N04.0727.1752.42649.htm
  | accessdate = 2008-01-05 }}
</ref> The ''Hurricane Packs'' were their ideas of letting players download additional game modes. The ''Packs'' were also free of charge. Itagaki said that as the ''Packs'' were born out of his team's interest, they did not care to charge players for their efforts.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Hurricane Pack Vol. 1 Q&A
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-07-16
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/531/531106p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-10 }}
</ref>

The two Packs were available over Xbox Live in the third quarter of 2004. ''Hurricane Pack&nbsp;1'' was a revamped version of Story Mode; Team Ninja tweaked the encounters and [[artificial intelligence]] (AI) of foes. The changes were to increase the difficulty of the game. The Pack also introduced foes such as humanoid cats, giants who wear ''[[Triceratops]]'' skulls, and [[cyborg]]s. Team Ninja made a key change to the camera system; players could control the camera and change the angle at which they view the scene.<ref name="hurhands1">{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Hurricane Pack Vol. 1 Hands-On
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-07-21
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/532/532309p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-10 }}
</ref> A unique feature of the Pack was the "Intercept" skill; this skill let players [[wikt:counter|counter]] any enemy attack with the proper timing.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Intercept
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-07-28
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/534/534280p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

''Hurricane Pack&nbsp;2'' kept the enhanced combat engine of the first ''Pack'', but took place in a world comprising only two regions. Players have to fight through several encounters to rescue Rachel from two new bosses, [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Nicchae]] and [[List of Ninja Gaiden characters#Fiends|Ishtaros]]. The ''Pack'' introduced the Lunar staff and fiends who wield giant swords and cast fireballs.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Hurricane Pack Vol. 2 Hands-On
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-09-22
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/550/550203p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-10 }}
</ref>

Team Ninja later compiled the ''Packs'' and added new features to create ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' (''Black''). The game, which Itagaki deemed as the final version of ''Ninja Gaiden'',<ref name="devint">{{cite web
  | author = Cory J. Herndon
  | title = Dev Interview: Tecmo w/Itagaki-san
  | publisher = Xbox.com
  | date = 2005-05-23
  | url = http://www.xbox.com/en-US/games/d/deadoralive4/20050523-tecmo.htm
  | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}
</ref> went on sale on [[September 20]], [[2005]].<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Black Ships to Retailers
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2005-09-21
  | url = http://64.78.9.175/press.asp?id=20
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}
</ref> A few years later, Team Ninja upgraded the graphics of the game and [[porting|ported]] it to the {{nowraplinks}}[[PlayStation 3]]{{nowraplinks end}} (PS3). Tecmo released this version as ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' (''Sigma'') on [[June 14]], [[2007]]. Black later became an [[Xbox Live Marketplace#Xbox Originals|Xbox Original]] game on [[February 11]], [[2008]].<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = New Xbox Originals on the Horizon
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2008-02-05
  | url = http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/849/849621p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-21 }}
</ref>

===Regional censorship===
<div style="font-size: 90%;float:right;border-left:1em solid white">
{| class="wikitable"
|+ Human beheadings featured
! &nbsp; !! [[NTSC-J]] !! [[NTSC#US_Video_Game_Region|NTSC-US]] !! [[PAL region|PAL]]
|-
! ''Ninja Gaiden''
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#FF90A8" | No
|-
! ''Ninja Gaiden Black''
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|-
! ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''
|align="center" bgcolor="#FF90A8" | No
|align="center" bgcolor="#A0F898" | Yes
|align="center" bgcolor="#FF90A8" | No
|}
</div>
''Ninja Gaiden'' contained bloody acts of violence, [[decapitation|beheadings]], and grotesque monsters in its uncensored form. As such, the North American games rating body, [[Entertainment Software Rating Board]], rated it as a "Mature" game.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Tor Thorsen
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Not for kids!
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-01-20
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaiden/news.html?sid=6086698
  | accessdate = 2008-02-11 }}
</ref> However, similar agencies in several other countries take a stricter view and consider beheadings as unsuitable content for young gamers.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Alex Navarro
  | title = Ninja Gaiden could get Euro makeover
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-03-11
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/6091272.html
  | accessdate = 2008-05-08 }}
</ref>

In [[Germany]], the [[Unterhaltungssoftware Selbstkontrolle]] (USK) deemed the beheadings in ''Ninja Gaiden'' excessive and refused to rate the game. This could put the game on the "[[Bundesprüfstelle für jugendgefährdende Medien#The List of Media Harmful to Young People|List of Media Harmful to Young People]]". Shops cannot put listed games on their shelves, nor advertise them. Furthermore, the shops can only sell these games on request to customers who are 18 years or older.<ref name="censor">{{cite web
  | author = Dan Chiappini 
  | title = Censory Overload&mdash;Australia vs. World
  | publisher = [[GameSpot|GameSpot AU]]
  | date = 2008-04-10
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/features/6188493/p-3.html
  | accessdate = 2008-04-26 }}
</ref> Hence, Tecmo censored the European [[PAL region|PAL]] version of ''Ninja Gaiden'' to obtain a USK rating.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = 1UP staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Censored In Europe
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | year = 2004
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/newsStory?cId=3125273
  | accessdate = 2008-05-04 }}
</ref> A year later, Tecmo managed to release ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' uncensored under a USK 18+ rating. However, they later released a censored version of ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma'' under the same rating.

[[Australia]]'s [[Office of Film and Literature Classification (Australia)|Office of Film and Literature Classification]] (OFLC) has stricter standards;<ref name="censor" /> its highest rating for video games, MA15+, meant such games have to be suitable for those 15 years and above. The sales of these games are also legally enforced. Very gory games, especially those with beheadings, tend not to qualify for this rating. If the game cannot qualify for MA15+, the OFLC will usually refuse to rate it. It is illegal to sell or own such games in Australia.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Dan Chiappini 
  | title = Censory Overload&mdash;History of AU Classification
  | publisher = [[GameSpot|GameSpot AU]]
  | date = 2008-04-01
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/features/6188493/index.html
  | accessdate = 2008-04-26 }}
</ref> As Tecmo never submitted ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' to OFLC for rating, the game never saw release in Australia.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Jeremy Jastrzab
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Review
  | publisher = [[PALGN|PAL Gaming Network]]
  | date = 2007-08-06
  | url = http://palgn.co.uk/article.php?id=8346
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = Chienne
  | title =  OFLC vs Xbox Originals = Casualty: Ninja Gaiden: Black
  | publisher = [[Internode Systems|Internode Games Network]]
  | date = 2008-02-13
  | url = http://games.internode.on.net/content.php?mode=news&id=2604
  | accessdate = 2008-03-21 }}
</ref>

Japan's [[Computer Entertainment Rating Organization]] (CERO) rated ''Ninja Gaiden'' and ''Black'', on their release, as 18+ games.<ref name="cesa">{{cite news
  | author = CESA staff
  | title = 旧18才以上対象ソフト再審査結果一覧（2006．05．30現在）
  | publisher = [[Computer Entertainment Supplier's Association]]
  | date = 2006-05-30
  | url = http://www.cesa.or.jp/news/2006/060530.pdf
  | format = PDF
  | language = {{Ja icon}}
  | accessdate = 2008-03-21 }}
</ref> At that time, CERO ratings acted as guidelines for consumers. However, on [[March 1]], [[2006]], the CERO rating system changed. CERO updated their ratings to a scale from A to D, and Z. Games with heavy amounts of gore and sexual content fall under the Z rating. The Z rating is also legally enforced; it is illegal to sell games rated Z to those under the age of 18.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = David Jenkins
  | title = Japan To Introduce Revised CERO Ratings System
  | publisher = [[Gamasutra]]
  | date = 2006-02-17
  | url = http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=8213
  | accessdate = 2008-02-10 }}
</ref> Tecmo took out the human beheadings in ''Sigma'' and got it a D rating for the [[East Asia]]n market. CERO also updated their ratings for the two previous games to D despite the games having human beheadings.<ref name="cesa" />
{{-}}

==Master Ninja Tournaments==
[[Image:MNT Game On.jpg|thumb|200px|left|The finalists played on walkways above the crowd while commentators talked about their actions on the big screen.]]
The Master Ninja Tournaments were three online contests held in 2004 by Microsoft and Tecmo. They took place over Xbox Live and were open to players in Europe, Japan, and North America. Players took part by uploading their scores of completed games to ranking boards.

The first two contests, Master Ninja Tournament 1 and 2, were also regional playoffs of the Ninja Gaiden Master Tournament World Championship. The championship was very popular; both playoffs broke the record for online participation of Xbox Live tournaments.<ref name="lotsninja">{{cite press release
  | title = Lots O' Ninjas
  | publisher = Digital Entertainment News
  | date = 2004-05-28
  | url = http://www.dignews.com/news.php?story_id=3686
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Breaks Records Again with Highest Registration Numbers
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-09-03
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaiden/news.html?sid=6106689&mode=press
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Players had 14 to 24&nbsp;days to complete the required games and submit their scores.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Stephen Coleman
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Registration Extended
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-08-03
  | url = http://games.ign.com/articles/535/535413p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = César Berardini
  | title = Tecmo Announces Master Ninja Tournament Round 2
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2004-07-12
  | url = http://news.teamxbox.com/xbox/6261/Tecmo-Announces-Master-Ninja-Tournament-Round-2/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://plusd.itmedia.co.jp/games/gsnews/0408/03/news09.html
  | title = 「Ninja Gaiden」世界大会の参加登録延長に
  | accessdate = 2008-03-25
  | author = Softbank Games staff
  | publisher = Softbank Games
  | date = 2004-08-03
  | language = {{Ja icon}} }}
</ref> Six of the highest scoring players in Europe and North America won [[bokken]]s bearing Itagaki's signature.<ref name="lotsninja">{{cite press release
  | title = Lots O' Ninjas
  | publisher = Digital Entertainment News
  | date = 2004-05-28
  | url = http://www.dignews.com/news.php?story_id=3686
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = César Berardini
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament for Europe Announced
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2004-07-26
  | url = http://news.teamxbox.com/xbox/6375/Master-Ninja-Tournament-for-Europe-Announced/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The playoff winners for each region also proceeded to the final. As Master Ninja Tournament 1 was not open to Europe, the region could only send one regional winner.

The playoffs were not without controversies. Players complained about Microsoft's tardiness in posting the official rules for the first playoff. They also deemed that the top score was not possible by fair means.<ref>{{cite journal
  | author = Xbox Nation staff
  | title = Ninja Nation
  | journal = Xbox Nation
  | pages = p. 28
  | publisher = [[Ziff Davis]]
  | location = California, United States
  | issn = 1538-9723
  | year = 2004
  | month = August
  | url = http://www.xbox-hq.com/html/modules.php?name=News&file=print&sid=1080
  | accessdate = 2007-09-05 }}
</ref> The officials, however, stated the score was possible and allowed the results to stand.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Hilary Goldstein
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Heats Up
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-05-26
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/519/519150p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> In the second playoff, Microsoft named the runner up as the winner for North America.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = César Berardini
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament Finals Details
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2004-09-15
  | url = http://news.teamxbox.com/xbox/6768/Master-Ninja-Tournament-Finals-Details/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> However, they sent the second runner up to the final.<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://plusd.itmedia.co.jp/games/tgs/2004/news/040925/07/index.html
  | title = Master Ninja Tournament 世界決勝戦 勝者は!?
  | accessdate = 2008-03-25
  | author = Softbank Games staff
  | publisher = Softbank Games
  | date = 2004-09-25
  | language = {{Ja icon}} }}
</ref>

The Ninja Gaiden Master Tournament World Championship final took place at [[Tokyo Game Show|Tokyo Game Show 2004]] on [[September 25]]. The five finalists played a custom game at the same time while commentators called out the action. They had 15&nbsp;minutes to clear the game and post the highest score. The champion emerged only in the last 20&nbsp;seconds when Yasunori Otsuka cleared the game and outscored the rest. At the prize ceremony, the finalists received their prize plaques from Itagaki.<ref>{{cite web
  | url = http://watch.impress.co.jp/game%2Fdocs/20040925/xbox3.htm
  | title = 世界一のNinja使いがここに決定! 「Master Ninja Tournament 世界決勝戦」がマイクロソフトブースで開催
  | accessdate = 2008-03-25
  | author = 平澤寿康
  | publisher = Game Watch
  | date = 2004-09-25
  | language = {{Ja icon}} }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = Chris Carle
  | title = TGS 2004: Ninja Gaiden Master Tournament World Championship
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2004-09-25
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/551/551186p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

Master Ninja Tournament 3 started on [[September 27]] and lasted 26&nbsp;days. It used the players' ''Hurricane Pack&nbsp;2'' scores to decide the rankings, and the prizes were Tecmo apparel and Team Ninja games.<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Tecmo Announces Third and Final Master Ninja Tournament, Hurricane Pack: Volume II
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-09-24
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaiden/news.html?sid=6108698&mode=press
  | accessdate = 2008-01-27 }}
</ref> Master Ninja Tournament 3 marked the end of official tournaments for ''Ninja Gaiden''. Although the tournaments have ended, Microsoft let the ranking boards remain active for players to upload their scores.
<br style="clear:both;"/>

==Remakes and merchandise==
Tecmo published two remakes of ''Ninja Gaiden'': ''Ninja Gaiden Black'' and ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''. They are at heart the same game as the original, telling the same story about Ryu and the Dark Dragon Blade. Itagaki deemed Black as the final version of ''Ninja Gaiden''.<ref name="devint" /> However, Tecmo brought the game to the PS3 and released ''Sigma'' as the last remake of ''Ninja Gaiden''.

===''Ninja Gaiden Black''===
Tecmo announced at E3 2005 that Team Ninja was working on ''Ninja Gaiden Black''.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Douglass C. Perry
  | title = E3 2005: Ninja Gaiden Black is Beautiful
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2005-05-20
  | url = http://xbox.ign.com/articles/618/618262p1.html
  | accessdate = 2008-05-11 }}
</ref> They later showed a working version of the game at Tokyo Game Show 2005.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Famitsu staff
  | title = 【ブース】『DOA4』の美麗映像に驚け！ テクモブースは例年以上の大混雑ぶり!!
  | publisher = ''[[Famitsu]]''
  | date = 2005-09-17
  | url = http://www.famitsu.com/game/event/2005/09/14/264,1126670828,43352,0,0.html
  | language = {{Ja icon}}
  | accessdate = 2008-05-04 }}
</ref> ''Black'' is a reworked compilation of ''Ninja Gaiden'' and the two ''Hurricane Packs''.<ref name="devint" /> The game featured new foes such as exploding bats and the doppelganger fiends who can imitate Ryu.<ref name="ngb1uprev">{{cite web
  | author = 1UP.com staff
  | title = Reviews: Ninja Gaiden Black
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2005-09-16
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/reviewPage?cId=3143860
  | accessdate = 2008-03-21 }}
</ref> It contained more costumes than ''Ninja Gaiden'', and swapped the [[Unlockable games|unlockable NES games]] for the [[Ninja Gaiden (arcade game)|arcade version]].<ref name="ngbpre">{{cite web
  | author = Rob Semsey
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Black Hands-On
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2005-08-10
  | url = http://previews.teamxbox.com/xbox/1143/Ninja-Gaiden-BLACK/p1/
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

One key feature was the two new difficulties: the easy Ninja Dog and very hard Master Ninja.<ref name="denngb" /> Itagaki added Ninja Dog after he heard complaints of ''Ninja Gaiden'' being too hard.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = James Mielke
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Black from 1UP.com
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2005-05-13
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=0&cId=3140456
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> However, he thought that any player could persist through the tough parts of the game and beat it.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = 1UP.com staff
  | title = Previews: Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[1UP.com]]
  | date = 2004-09-05
  | url = http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3061511
  | accessdate = 2007-09-23 }}
</ref> Hence, he made ''Black'' put on a mocking tone for those playing on Ninja Dog; the players receive pink ribbons as accessories and watch Ayane treat Ryu as an inferior. Itagaki also made the other difficulties in ''Black'' harder than they were in ''Ninja Gaiden''. He changed the foes to be stronger and more aggressive and toned down moves that were too powerful such as the Flying Swallow.<ref name="denngb" />

Another key feature of ''Black'' is Mission Mode, which comprised 50&nbsp;missions of pure combat action. One mission is adapted from the game played in the Ninja Gaiden Master Tournament World Championship final. Furthermore, the last five missions linked together to compose Eternal Legend; this linked series of missions was a revamped ''Hurricane Pack&nbsp;2'' using the game engine of ''Black''.<ref name="ngbpre" />

===''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''===
In 2006, Tecmo and Sony announced the development of Ninja Gaiden Sigma for the PS3.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Andy Robinson
  | title = Ninja Gaiden pulls a flying kick on PS3
  | publisher = ''[[Computer and Video Games]]''
  | date = 2006-09-20
  | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=146205
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = Tim Surette
  | coauthors = Brendan Sinclair
  | title = TGS 06: Gaiden, Shirokishi lead new PS3 game charge
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2006-09-21
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/events/tgs2006/story.html?sid=6158162&pid=935677
  | accessdate = 2008-05-04 }}
</ref> [[Eidos Interactive|Eidos]] got the European publishing rights for this game.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Andy Robinson
  | title = Eidos picks up Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = ''[[Computer and Video Games]]''
  | date = 2007-04-18
  | url = http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=162227
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Itagaki had no direct role in this remake and judged it as a flawed game.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Jon Wilcox
  | title = Itagaki: Ninja Gaiden 2 Is My Final Instalment News
  | publisher = Total Video Games
  | date = 2008-05-13
  | url = http://www.totalvideogames.com/news/Itagaki_Ninja_Gaiden_2_Is_My_Final_Instalment_13219_7010_0.htm
  | accessdate = 2008-05-14 }}
</ref> He, however, said that ''Sigma'' was to let PlayStation owners have a taste of ''Ninja Gaiden''.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Anoop Gantayat
  | title = No Sigma For 360
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-06-01
  | url = http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/793/793679p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

The [[Cell (microprocessor)|Cell processor]] of the PS3 let Team Ninja overhaul the game to use larger and more detailed [[Texture mapping|textures]].<ref name="sigpre" /> The game world also had a few changes. The team added a few new areas and several save points and shops.<ref name="gssigrev" /> Changes to the game engine let players shoot arrows in midair, fight on water surfaces, and play as Rachel in a few chapters and missions.<ref name="sigpre" /><ref name="gssigpre">{{cite web
  | author = Gabe Graziani
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Preview
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-05-25
  | url = http://ps3.gamespy.com/playstation-3/ninja-gaiden-sigma/792132p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-06 }}
</ref> Players can also shake the [[PlayStation 3 accessories#Sixaxis|Sixaxis]] controller to increase the power of their ninpos.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Rob Fahey
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = 2007-06-16
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=77792
  | accessdate = 2008-01-27 }}
</ref> Team Ninja added foes and bosses such as bikers, fish-men, and Gamov. They also added a pair of katanas called the Dragon's Claw and Tiger's Fang.<ref name="sigpre" /><ref name="gssigrev">{{cite web
  | author = Kevin VanOrd
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma for PlayStation 3 Review
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2007-07-02
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/ps3/action/ninjagaidensigma/review.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> Although marketed as the "more complete" version of Ninja Gaiden,<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Walt Wyman
  | title = TGS 06: PS3 Ninja Gaiden Detailed
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2007-09-22
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/6158343.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>
{{cite news
  | author = Anoop Gantayat
  | title = Confirmed: Ninja Gaiden on PS3
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2006-09-20
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/733/733714p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = Rob Burman
  | title = Eidos Unleashing Ninjas in Europe
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-04-20
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/782/782234p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> ''Sigma'' left out several features found in the Xbox games. It did not have the opening movie or the unlockable games. It also had fewer costumes than ''Black'' did.<ref name="sigpre" /><ref name="gssigpre" /><ref name="ignau">{{cite web 
  | author = Patrick Kolan
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma AU Review
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-07-04
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/801/801548p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref>

In Japan, Tecmo engaged a local-based singer, [[Leah Dizon]], to promote the game. Aside from appearing in a commercial and singing its song,<ref>{{cite video
  | year = 2007
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Japan TV Commercial
  | url = http://www.gametrailers.com/player/usermovies/69850.html
  | format = flv
  | medium = Television commercial
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> she signed posters that Tecmo gave away at the launch of the game.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Famitsu staff
  | title = リア･ディゾンのサイン入りポスターがもらえる！　『NINJA GAIDEN Σ』発売記念イベントが開催決定
  | publisher = ''[[Famitsu]]''
  | date = 2007-06-11
  | url = http://www.famitsu.com/game/news/2007/06/11/103,1181556863,73212,0,0.html
  | language = {{Ja icon}}
  | accessdate = 2008-05-03 }}
</ref> In North America, [[GameStop]] sold [[special edition]]s of ''Sigma'' in their stores.<ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Tecmo Announces the Launch of Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2007-07-02
  | url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2007_July_2/ai_n19330371
  | accessdate = 2008-05-03 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news
  | author = Rob Purchese
  | title = Sigma Special Edition iffy for Europe
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = 2007-04-24
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=75667
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref name="cejp">{{cite news
  | author = Ten-Four
  | title =  海外レビューハイスコア『Ninja Gaiden Sigma』
  | publisher = Game Spark
  | date = 2007-07-05
  | url = http://www.gamespark.jp/modules/news/index.php?p=2886
  | accessdate = 2008-03-21
  | language = {{Ja icon}} }}
</ref> They claimed that the special edition had an exclusive "behind-the-scenes" [[DVD]] and a code to unlock extra missions. The code, however, proved to be usable on normal copies of the game.<ref name="cejp" /><ref>{{cite book
  | title = Codes & Cheats
  | origdate = 2007-11-15
  | edition = Winter 2008
  | publisher = [[Prima Games]]
  | location = California, US
  | isbn = 0-761-55668-0 }}
</ref>

Tecmo released a demo and a new game mode, Survival Mode, for ''Sigma'' over the [[PlayStation Network]].<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Anoop Gantayat
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Downloadable Content Announced
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-08-03
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/810/810350p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref> The demo limited players to the first chapter of the game but let them play as Rachel in a separate mission.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Richard Leadbetter
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = [[Eurogamer]]
  | date = 2007-05-02
  | url = http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=75934
  | accessdate = 2008-04-21 }}
</ref> Survival Mode comprised missions in which players keep fighting until they have killed all the foes or their character has died.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Chris Roper
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Expansion Pack Hands-on
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-09-06
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/818/818522p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-06 }}
</ref>

===Merchandise===
Tecmo has built up a line of merchandise around the ''Ninja Gaiden'' name. Its online shop carries apparel and accessories such as caps, wristbands, T-shirts, key holders, and mugs. Most of the merchandise is associated with the launch of the ''Ninja Gaiden'' games or given as prizes in the Master Ninja Tournaments.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Justin Calvert
  | title = Tecmo releases Ninja Gaiden merchandise
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2003-12-19
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/news/6085935.html
  | accessdate = 2008-05-03 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite press release
  | title = Tecmo Announces Free Retro T-Shirt As Ninja Gaiden Black Pre-Order Incentive
  | publisher = [[Tecmo]]
  | date = 2005-09-01
  | url = http://64.78.9.175/press.asp?id=18
  | accessdate = 2007-08-23 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Jack DeVries
  | title = Ottsel's Blog&mdash;In-game reservation gifts: Completely worthless
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-07-05
  | url = http://blogs.ign.com/Ottsel/2007/07/05/59292/
  | accessdate = 2008-05-03 }}
</ref> Tecmo has also published the original soundtrack of the game under their record label, Wake Up, on [[March 20]], [[2004]]. Kotobukiya, a figurine maker, had [[1:6 scale modeling|1/6th scale]] [[Model figure|plastic figures]] of ''Ninja Gaiden'' characters in their range of products. As of 2007, they have produced figures of Ryu, Ayane, Kureha, and Rachel.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Kotobukiya USA staff
  | title = Ninja Gaiden ARTFX Statues
  | publisher = Kotobukiya USA
  | date = n.d.
  | url = http://www.kotous.com/video-games/ninja-gaiden.php
  | accessdate = 2007-08-27 }}
</ref>

