|<center>''Ninja Gaiden''<br />''Sigma''
|colspan=3|<center>IGN's Game of the Month<ref>{{cite web
  | author = IGN PlayStation Team
  | title = Game of the Month: July 2007
  | publisher = [[IGN]]
  | date = 2007-07-31
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/809/809607p1.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-05 }}
</ref>
|}{{*}} score out of 5
</div>
''Ninja Gaiden'' received a lot of critical acclaim. [[GameSpot]] called it as "one of the best most challenging action adventure games ever made".<ref name="gsngrev" /> [[IGN]] said that it "sets a new standard for third-person action games in terms of length, depth, speed, and gore".<ref name="ignngrev" /> Critics also put forward the game as one of the most difficult games up to 2007.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Danny Cowan
  | title = Critical Reception: Tecmo/Team Ninja's Ninja Gaiden Sigma
  | publisher = [[Gamasutra]]
  | date = 2007-07-04
  | url = http://previews.teamxbox.com/xbox/1143/Ninja-Gaiden-BLACK/p1/
  | accessdate = 2007-12-13 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = Rob Semsey
  | title = Ninja Gaiden: Black Hands-On
  | publisher = [[TeamXbox]]
  | date = 2005-08-10
  | url = http://previews.teamxbox.com/xbox/1143/Ninja-Gaiden-BLACK/p1/
  | accessdate = 2007-12-13 }}
</ref> Its remake, ''Ninja Gaiden Black'', still impressed critics. GameSpot hailed it for having the best visual and audio presentation on the Xbox. They also praised its new feature, Mission Mode, for "[distilling] the game down to its purest essentials".<ref name="gsngbrev" /> IGN called its release as "a rare and welcome day", which "[brought their] excitement levels back to the first time [they] played the game".<ref name="ignngbrev" />

From a technical point of view, critics regarded ''Ninja Gaiden'' and ''Black'' as the best of Xbox software; they pushed the console hardware to its limits without showing significant drops in performance. GameSpot was impressed with their "first-rate presentation" and said that none of the games at that time came close in visuals and audios.<ref name="gsngbrev" /> IGN said the games could "make [them] momentarily forget about the next generation of consoles".<ref name="ignngbrev" /> ''Ninja Gaiden'' and ''Black'' were top-selling Xbox games, which led to them being [[backward compatibility|compatible]] with the [[Xbox 360]] for all regions on its release.<ref>{{cite news 
  | author = Tor Thorsen
  | title = 360 to play 200-plus Xbox games
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2005-11-11
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/halo2/news.html?sid=6139702
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news 
  | author = Hirohiko Niizumi
  | title = Xbox 360 backward compatibility lacking in Japan
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2005-11-16
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/ninjagaidenblack/news.html?sid=6139921
  | accessdate = 2007-08-21 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite news 
  | author = Brendan Sinclair
  | title = European 360 backward compatibility detailed
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2005-11-17
  | url = http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/halo2/news_6140002.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref>

However, critics varied in their views on the technical aspects of ''Ninja Gaiden Sigma''. The gaming site, [[1UP.com]], called the updated graphics as "a gorgeous reworking of the modern ninja classic".<ref name="sig1uprev" /> [[Pro-G]], however, said that they were average by next-generation standards and showed occasional "tearing, jagged edges, and miss matched collision between bloodstains and walls".<ref name="prosigrev" /> Various flaws also troubled 1UP. They encountered frequent loadings, even in combat despite installing the game on the local hard drive. They also saw visual glitches such as [[screen tearing]] when the camera moved. These flaws made the game "feel like a bit of a slapdash port".<ref name="sig1uprev" />

Although critics praised ''Sigma'' for retaining the gameplay in the previous games,<ref name="ignau" /><ref name="sig1uprev" /> its lack of new attractive features made them question its worth as "a remake of a remake". Pro-G said that ''Sigma'' was not worth a full priced game because it "has, in effect, been available for years in one form or another".<ref name="prosigrev" /> [[Eurogamer]] stated that ''Sigma'' lacked the "wow factor" when compared to ''God of War'' and ''[[God of War II|its sequel]]''.<ref name="eusigrev" /> The 1UP critic said that shaking the Sixaxis to power up a ninpo was "silly" and a "foolishly tacked-on" way to use the controller.<ref name="sig1uprev" /> IGN was not excited about playing as Rachel and wished to "get back to Ryu's sections simply because he's more fun to play".<ref name="ignsigrev" /> DailyGame, however, said that her slow pace brings "much-needed respite for newcomers and provide something new for experienced players".<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Martin Ray
  | title = Ninja Gaiden Sigma Review
  | publisher = DailyGame
  | date = 2007-08-15
  | url = http://www.dailygame.net/news/archives/006499.php
  | accessdate = 2007-08-27 }}
</ref>

A common criticism of the ''Ninja Gaiden'' games was with the camera. The default camera system centers the action on Ryu and his surroundings. It has also improved with the use of manual controls since the ''Hurricane Packs''.<ref name="hurhands1" /><ref name="gsngbrev" /> There are, however, times when the camera locks on to an object and loses track of Ryu, which made the critics mad.<ref name="ignngbrev" /><ref name="entdep" /><ref name="trend" /> However, most critics judged that either the camera was usually decent or the gameplay was good enough to cover up its flaws.<ref name="gsngbrev" /><ref name="ignsigrev" />

The ''Ninja Gaiden'' games gained a reputation throughout the gaming community for their difficulty and details.<ref name="history" /><ref>{{cite journal
  | author = Ray Huling
  | year = 2007
  | month = October
  | title = Ninja Playground
  | journal = [[The Brooklyn Rail]]
  | url = http://brooklynrail.org/2007/10/streets/ninja-playground
  | accessdate = 2007-10-12 }}
</ref> Although they appealed to gamers who are like Pro-G in wanting a "bloody hard, but also bloody good" challenge,<ref name="prongrev" /> casual gamers might find the learning curve daunting. IGN warned that gamers with lesser skills might not "get as much out of this game as others due to [its] incredible difficulty".<ref name="ignngbrev" /> Clive Thompson focused on ''Ninja Gaiden'' in his ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' article on the rewards of beating difficult games. He said that there are games so hard that players get mad in trying to beat them and stay mad even after doing so. ''Ninja Gaiden'', however, rewarded players who beat the game; it brought them "a sort of exhausted exhilaration, like finally reaching the end of ''[[War and Peace]]''". The game was a success in striking balance between challenge and reward.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Clive Thompson
  | title = Ninja Gaiden
  | publisher = [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]
  | date = 2004-05-06
  | url = http://www.slate.com/id/2100116/
  | accessdate = 2007-09-05 }}
</ref>

Consumers have bought 1.5&nbsp;million copies of ''Ninja Gaiden'' and ''Black'' as of August 2007.<ref>{{cite news
  | author = Kotaro Tsunetomi
  | title = テクモが急騰、業績予想を増額－「ＮＩＮＪＡ ＧＡＩＤＥＮ」好調
  | publisher = [[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] Japan
  | date = 2007-07-06
  | url = http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=90001002&sid=azaEyzbR0k7w&refer=jp_home
  | accessdate = 2007-09-02
  | language = {{Ja icon}} }}
</ref> The sale figures reflected Tecmo's decision to design and cater the game for foreign gamers. The Japanese were not excited over the games. According to Itagaki, they bought 60,000&nbsp;copies of ''Ninja Gaiden'' in the four months since its release.<ref name="giint" /> ''Famitsu'' also wrote that ''Sigma'' sold 76,095&nbsp;copies in its first six months.<ref>{{cite journal
  | author = Famitsu Marketing Data Service
  | year = January
  | month = 2008
  | title = Top 100 sales
  | journal = 2007 Yearly Report
  | publisher = [[Famitsu]]
  | location = Tokyo, Japan
  | url = http://ps3.ign.com/articles/845/845026p2.html
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref> However, according to the [[NPD Group]], the games saw great sales in the United States; in their first month, ''Ninja Gaiden'' sold 362,441&nbsp;copies and ''Sigma'' sold 63,637&nbsp;copies.<ref>{{cite journal
  | author = NPD Tech
  | year = 2004
  | month = March
  | title = NPD US Sales Data
  | publisher = [[NPD Group]]
  | location = New York, United States
  | url = http://www.3dnews.ru/games/games-weekly-27042004/index2.htm
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite journal
  | author = NPD Group
  | year = 2007
  | month = June
  | title = NPD US Sales Data
  | publisher = [[NPD Group]]
  | location = New York, United States
  | url = http://www.cubed3.com/news/8201
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref> ''[[Next Generation]]'' also claimed that consumers bought 470,000&nbsp;copies of ''Sigma'' in Europe and North America as of April 2008.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = Next Generation staff
  | title = The Top 100 Selling Games of the Last 12 Months
  | publisher = ''[[Next Generation Magazine]]''
  | date = 2008-04-09
  | url = http://www.next-gen.biz/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=9639&Itemid=2
  | accessdate = 2008-04-10 }}
</ref> The critical and commercial successes of ''Ninja Gaiden'' have led [[CNET]] and GameSpot Asia to induct the game into their Halls of Fame.<ref>{{cite web
  | author = David Rudden
  | title = Gaming hall of fame: the Xbox's best games
  | publisher = [[CNet]]
  | date = 2006-06-16
  | url = http://reviews.cnet.com/4321-9582_7-6509238.html
  | accessdate = 2007-09-05 }}
</ref><ref>{{cite web
  | author = GameSpot Asia staff
  | title = Editor's Choice Hall of Fame
  | publisher = [[GameSpot]]
  | date = 2004-04-23
  | url = http://web.archive.org/web/20050406025443/www.gamespotasia.com/pcgames/features/story/0,2000006896,30076524,00.htm
  | accessdate = 2008-02-03 }}
</ref>
